ARTICLE
summary:      The theory of relativity, developed by Albert Einstein, encompasses two interrelated physics theories: special relativity (1905) and general relativity (1915). Special relativity deals with the physics of objects moving at constant speeds near the speed of light. General relativity is a theory of gravitation that describes gravity as the curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy.
claims:
  - Special relativity (1905) postulates that the laws of physics are the same in all inertial reference frames and the speed of light in vacuum is constant (approximately 299,792,458 m/s)
  - The mass-energy equivalence relation E=mc2 follows from special relativity
  - Time dilation means moving clocks tick more slowly relative to stationary observers
  - Length contraction means objects appear shorter along the direction of motion at relativistic speeds
  - General relativity (1915) describes gravity as curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy
  - General relativity predicted gravitational lensing, gravitational time dilation, and gravitational waves
  - Gravitational waves were first directly detected by LIGO in September 2015
evidence:     Solar eclipse observations (Eddington, 1919) confirmed light bending. GPS satellites require relativistic corrections. LIGO detected gravitational waves (Abbott et al., 2016 — Nobel Prize 2017). Perihelion precession of Mercury explained.
limitations:  General relativity is incompatible with quantum mechanics at the Planck scale. A theory of quantum gravity remains unresolved. Singularities (black holes, Big Bang) indicate breakdown of the theory.
methodology:  Encyclopedic synthesis of theoretical physics literature
---
NOTES
Einstein's 1905 paper "On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies" introduced special relativity. General relativity replaced Newton's law of universal gravitation and is the current best description of gravitation. GPS satellites must account for both special relativistic time dilation (clocks run slower due to velocity) and general relativistic effects (clocks run faster at higher altitude) — a net gain of about 38 microseconds per day.